<section class="block-section story">
  <span class="section-tag">Story</span>
  <h2>Why this block matters</h2>
  <p class="sub">One block between you and the NASA Committee defense. Today is rehearsal.</p>
  <p>Your draft is complete (or close to it). Tomorrow you defend it for 2 minutes of peer Q&A as part of a 6-minute presentation slot. The Q&A is where most students lose points — not because they don't know their material, but because they meet a question they haven't rehearsed and freeze. Today fixes that. The Q&A Bank in the assessment package has six question categories that peers will draw from tomorrow. By the end of today, you've rehearsed against all six.</p>
  <p>The six categories: <strong>(1) Clarification</strong> — "What did you mean when you said…?" <strong>(2) Evidence + source</strong> — "What's your source for that?" <strong>(3) Trade-off / comparative</strong> — "Why this exoplanet over Mars or TRAPPIST-1 e?" <strong>(4) Uncertainty</strong> — "What's your biggest unknown? How confident are you?" <strong>(5) Implementation / observation</strong> — "What would you point JWST at next?" <strong>(6) Devil's-advocate</strong> — "Convince me the science return justifies the cost." Different categories ask for different cognitive moves — vary your rehearsal across all six.</p>
  <p>Today the <strong>Defense Practice Partner</strong> joins your toolkit. It role-plays a NASA evaluation committee member. It will ask you the question your study-partner won't — the one you've been avoiding. Use it for any category your Pair rehearsal didn't cover.</p>
</section>

